drug.name: Alaproclate
drug.description: Alaproclate was developed as one of the first selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor (SSRI) antidepressants by Astra AB (now AstraZeneca) in the 1970s. Development was discontinued due to concerns over hepatotoxicity observed in animal studies. Alaproclate has also been found to act as a non-competitive NMDA receptor antagonist although without discriminative stimulus properties similar to phencyclidine.

article.citation: Wilkinson A, Courtney M, Westlind-Danielsson A, Hallnemo G, Akerman KE: Alaproclate acts as a potent, reversible and noncompetitive antagonist of the NMDA receptor coupled ion flow. J Pharmacol Exp Ther. 1994 Dec;271(3):1314-9.

Nicholson KL, Balster RL: Evaluation of the phencyclidine-like discriminative stimulus effects of novel NMDA channel blockers in rats. Psychopharmacology (Berl). 2003 Nov;170(2):215-24. Epub 2003 Jul 8.

classification.description: This compound belongs to the class of organic compounds known as alpha amino acid esters. These are ester derivatives of alpha amino acids.
